1.  Thread kya hota hai?
    Thread ek process ke andar ek chhota execution path hai. Jaise MS Word mein ek thread typing handle karta hai,
    doosra spell-check karta hai — dono ek hi process ke part hain aur memory share karte hain.
    Interview Tip: One liner: Process = full gaana, Thread = ek instrument us gaane mein.

2.  Process aur Thread mein kya difference hai?
    Process apna khud ka memory space rakhta hai, isolated hota hai, aur heavy hota hai. Thread ek process ke andar hota hai,
    memory share karta hai, lightweight hota hai aur faster communicate karta hai. Context switch bhi thread mein fast hota hai.
    Interview Tip: Interview mein: "Process = alag flat, Thread = ek flat mein roommates."

3.  Multithreaded programming ke kya benefits hain?
    Application responsive rehta hai (ek thread block ho toh doosra chalta rehta hai), resources efficiently use hote hain kyunki
    memory share hoti hai, multicore CPUs ka pura fayda milta hai, aur server performance better hoti hai.
    Interview Tip: 4 benefits yaad karo: Responsive, Resource-sharing, Multicore, Server-speed.

4.  Multithreading ke advantages kya hain?
    Improved throughput, efficient multiprocessor use, better responsiveness (UI freeze nahi hoti), enhanced server performance
    (ek slow request doosro ko block nahi karta), lower resource usage (shared memory), faster thread-to-thread communication.
    Interview Tip: 6 benefits: Throughput, Multicore, Responsive, Server, Resource, Speed.

5.  Multithreading vs Multitasking mein kya fark hai?
    Multithreading = ek process ke andar multiple threads. Lightweight, memory share. Process ki feature. 
    Multitasking = multiple processes/programs concurrently. Heavyweight. OS ki feature. Dono CPU switching use karte hain 
    but different level pe.
    Interview Tip: Level difference: Multithreading = inside process. Multitasking = between processes.

6.  User-level aur Kernel-level threads mein kya fark hai?
    User-level: User space mein implement, OS nahi jaanta, fast context switch, no hardware support needed.
    BUT ek thread block ho toh poora process block.
    Kernel-level: OS implement karta hai, OS aware hai, ek block ho dusra chale, lekin context switch slow.
    Interview Tip: Modern OS: Hybrid use karta hai — N:M model. Java threads = kernel-level on most OS.

7.  User-level thread block hone pe kya hota hai?
    User-level thread agar blocking system call kare toh poora process block ho jaata hai — OS sirf process ko jaanta hai,
    individual threads ko nahi. Isliye many-to-one model mein ek thread ki blocking operation se sab suffer karte hain.
    Kernel-level threads mein aisa nahi hota.
    Interview Tip: Solution: Jacketing = blocking call ko non-blocking version mein wrap karo, ya kernel threads use karo.
    

